# DVRTC Environment Configuration
# Used as the template for .env
# ./scripts/setup_networking.sh will create .env from this file if it does not exist

# ============================================================================
# REQUIRED SETTINGS
# ============================================================================

# PUBLIC_IPV4: Your server's public IPv4 address
# This is used for SIP and RTP signaling
# - DO NOT use 127.0.0.1 (calls won't work)
# - Use the IPv4 address that clients should use to reach this host
# - Prefer ./scripts/setup_networking.sh to detect and set it automatically
# Example: PUBLIC_IPV4=192.168.1.100
PUBLIC_IPV4=

# ============================================================================
# OPTIONAL NETWORK SETTINGS
# ============================================================================

# PUBLIC_IPV6: Your server's external IPv6 address (optional, opt-in)
# When set, DVRTC exposes the external-facing services over IPv6 as well
# - Use the raw IPv6 literal without brackets
# - Do not use ::1 or link-local fe80:: addresses here
# Example: PUBLIC_IPV6=2001:db8::1
PUBLIC_IPV6=

# ============================================================================
# CERTIFICATE SETTINGS (Optional - for TLS/HTTPS)
# ============================================================================

# DOMAIN: Fully qualified domain name for LetsEncrypt certificates
# Leave blank to use self-signed certificates (recommended for lab use)
# If set, certbot will automatically request LetsEncrypt certificates
# Requirements:
#   - Domain must point to this server's IP
#   - Port 80 must be accessible from internet
#   - Email must be set
# Example: DOMAIN=dvrtc.example.com
DOMAIN=

# EMAIL: Email address for LetsEncrypt notifications
# Only required if DOMAIN is set
# LetsEncrypt will send certificate expiration warnings here
# Example: EMAIL=admin@example.com
EMAIL=

# ============================================================================
# DATABASE CREDENTIALS
# ============================================================================
# IMPORTANT: Run ./scripts/generate_passwords.sh to generate these automatically
# MYSQL_PORT: Host port for MySQL (default: 23306)
# Non-standard port to avoid easy discovery
# MYSQL_PORT=23306

# DO NOT manually set these - use the generation script

# MYSQL_ROOT_PASSWORD: MySQL root password (auto-generated)
# This is a strong random password for the MySQL root account
MYSQL_ROOT_PASSWORD=

# SIPCALLER1_PASSWORD: Password for internal SIP caller (auto-generated)
# Used by call generator (baresip-callgen) for automated calling
SIPCALLER1_PASSWORD=

# ============================================================================
# INTENTIONALLY VULNERABLE CREDENTIALS (Hardcoded in Docker Compose)
# ============================================================================
# These credentials are INTENTIONALLY WEAK and part of the training environment
# They are hardcoded in docker-compose.yml and configs - DO NOT change them here:
#
# MySQL Database:
#   - User: kamailio
#   - Password: kamailiorw (HARDCODED - intentionally weak)
#   - Port: 23306 by default (EXPOSED - intentionally vulnerable, configurable via MYSQL_PORT)
#
# SIP Extensions:
#   - Extension 1000: Password 1500 (weak - for cracking exercises)
#   - Extension 2000: Password 2000 (digest leak demonstration)
#
# coturn:
#   - Username: user
#   - Password: joshua (hardcoded)
#   - CLI Password: coturn (hardcoded)
#
# These are part of the intentional vulnerabilities and should NOT be changed
# unless you know what you're doing and update all related configs.

# ============================================================================
# SETUP INSTRUCTIONS
# ============================================================================
# 1. Auto-detect and set PUBLIC_IPV4 (and PUBLIC_IPV6 if available):
#    ./scripts/setup_networking.sh
#
# 2. Generate secure passwords:
#    ./scripts/generate_passwords.sh
#
# 3. Generate certificates:
#    For self-signed (recommended):
#      ./scripts/init-selfsigned.sh
#    For LetsEncrypt (if DOMAIN and EMAIL are set):
#      ./scripts/init-letsencrypt.sh
#
# 4. Validate configuration (recommended):
#    ./scripts/validate_env.sh
#    This checks for missing passwords, invalid settings, and required cert files
#
# 5. Start DVRTC:
#    docker compose up -d
#
# 6. Verify services are running:
#    docker compose ps

# ============================================================================
# TROUBLESHOOTING
# ============================================================================
# - If services fail to start, check docker compose logs
# - Ensure PUBLIC_IPV4 is set correctly (not 127.0.0.1)
# - Make sure ports are not in use (5060, 23306, 80, 443, etc.)
# - Run generate_passwords.sh if credentials are empty
# - Run setup_networking.sh if PUBLIC_IPV4 or PUBLIC_IPV6 is wrong or empty
# - Run init-selfsigned.sh if validate_env.sh reports missing certificates
# - See docs/troubleshooting.md for detailed help
